\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 2nd September, 1943 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (Covering period from 24th to 31st August, 1943
\par 
\par I. GENERAL COMMENTS }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (No reports have been received since the Prime Minister's speech of August 31)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 1.  GENERAL STATE OF CONFIDENCE AND REACTION TO NEWS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par Confidence remains high as a result of the Russian successes, the air offensive - particularly on Berlin, and the evidence of unrest in occupied countries.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
In spite of the good news, however, there appears to have been a slight drop in spirits since last week, showing itself in: 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid11883990 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
(a) Widespread uneasiness over British and U.S. relations with Russia; this has increased since last week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (b) Impatience at Allied inactivity, both not invading the Continent "to give more concrete help to the Russians", and in "riot driving Italy out of the war".
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7484735 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par At the same time, there continues to be good deal of expectati
on that "something big is brewing", though speculation is less than a week ago. Although there are still many optimists who think the war will be over by Christmas, there is an increasing tendency to put back the date of final victory to next year, and a 
minority say that "the war is only beginning now".}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par Home Front. The hope that this will be the last winter of the war appears to be reducing dread of the black-out, but dislike of it is very strong; people are asking whether black-out conditions could 
be modified and whether -.cycle and torch batteries Will be in reasonable supply this year.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 The greatest home front worry still appears to be footwear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.10.11.13. 17 passim.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 No report from Region 9 this week.)
\par 
\par 2. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 RUSSIA AND THE OTHER ALLIES}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par Suspicion and anxiety that all is not well between Russia and the English-speaking Allies, already' widespread 1st week, have increased.
\par 
\par Russia's apparent lack of appreciation of our}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 effort and our help to her, the recall of MM. Mai
sky and Litvinov, and, above all, the absence of any Russian representative at Quebec, are "linked as evidence that friction exists between Russia on the one hand and U.S.A. and ourselves on the other".}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 Talk of the possibility of Russia making a separate p
eace with Germany is reported from six Regions. On the causes  of disagreement, two main viewpoints are apparent (agar from minority who blame both sides or neither) :}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid11883990 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (a) 
Those who consider that Russia has every reason to be dissatisfied, because:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li851\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin851\itap0\pararsid11883990 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
(i) We have not started a large-scale Continental landing to relieve German pressure. Even many who arc "far from friendly to Russia" say we have had  ample time to build up and plan a major offensive, and that "to offer Sicily as our contribution is an
 affront to Russia and dishonour to ourselves", They add that "if we don't do something big soon to divert Axis forces from Russia, we shall have only ourselves to blame if she takes the view that we are hoping to win the war at her expense, finishing up 
fresh and powerful while she is exhausted and weak".
\par 
\par (ii) There is little sympathy with Russia among "highly placed officials and influential people", and still loss appreciation of what she has done. This view is held by workers especially. There are "rumours of a whispering campaign against Russia", a
nd it is feared that "the reluctance of the high-ups - but not Mr. Churchill - to work with Russia will lead to a breach and actual war with her later on".}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
In Orkney, "it is firmly believed that the defenses being constructed there are designed for future}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5447783  conflict with Russia }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 rather than Germany".
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid11883990 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (b) Those who, while appreciating all Russia is doing, fool that she is unreasonable, because:
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li851\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin851\itap0\pararsid11883990 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
(i) The Russians have not given enough credit to the other Allies for their help - by providing supplies, s
ometimes to our own disadvantage, by our heavy bombing policy, and by holding troops in the west to meet the invasion throat. People particularly fool that the Russians don't understand naval power, or "the difficulty of transporting troops and material b
y sea".
\par 
\par (ii) Stalin is "cynically indifferent to everything but Russian ambitions". It is pointed cut that Russia left us alone in 1940 while she had a pact with Germany, and is still at peace with J}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
apan while we have to fight her.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11883990 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 Whatever reasons
 are suggested to account for lack of co-operation, its possibility is almost universally deplored. It is widely hoped that:
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid11883990 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par (a)  A conference between the three powers can be arranged to take place at an early date, to bring about "open and friendly co-operation and ensure peaceful European settlement hereafter". (Nine Regions)
\par 
\par (b) Mr. Churchill would throw some light on the subject in his speech
\par (Five Regions), and make it clear that we are really one with Russia in the present struggle".
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7484735 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (1.2.3.4.5.5SR.6.7.8.10.11.13)
\par 
\par 3. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 THE RUSSIAN OFFENSIVE }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par General pleasure is reported at the capture of Taganrog, following on that of Kharkov. Admiration for the Red Army already great, is said to be increasing, and there is gratitude for "all she 
is saving us" and "restlessness that we are doing so little to help".
\par 
\par Many expect further advances; some think "the Ukraine may be 'Captured by the end of the summer campaign", even that, "during the next few months, the Russians may be able to free most of their country".
\par 
\par There is also speculation as to what Russia will do then. Some think she may stop at her borders and negotiate a separate peace, others that she will march through Poland into Germany; it is asked "what will happen in this count
ry .if Russia gets to Berlin first?"}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (1.2.3.4.5.5SR.6.7.8.10.11.13.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 17 two provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 4. THE NEXT MOVES}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par Expectation that an Allied invasion of the Continent is imminent continues, but there appears to be less certainty about it this week and, in view of Russia's need, more impatience.
\par 
\par Discussion is, however, not quite as widespread as it was, but the majority still find plenty of evidence to support their belief that it will take place before long, many thinking that "the balloon will go up when the Prime Minister returns".
\par 
\par There is considerable disappointment that "we have reached September without any large European front being opened". People are impatient that "the Sicilian success was not followed_ by a quick attack on Italy", and fear that our delay is allowing the 
enemy to strengthen his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 defences}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 . There is impatience at the apparent lull after each new move we make.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 Some suspect that the U.S.A. is more interested in the Far Eastern than the European war, and may "insist on the second front being against the Japanese".
\par 
\par At the same time, most people, whether confident or disappointed, seem "content to leave it to our leaders", fooling that "further preparations are worth waiting for if those are essential to a more complete success'. Speculation as to "whore" is o
n exactly the same lines as last week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.10.11.15.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 17 two provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 5. THE ALLIED ARE OFFENSIVE}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par (No reports have been received since the 'Berlin raid of August 31/September 1.)
\par 
\par Satisfaction with our massive raids" on enemy territory continues, and so does praise for, and pride in, the men of the R.A.F. It is felt that our "terrific rounding" of Germany must by having}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5447783  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 its effect on German morale, and it is thought that "signs of demoralisation and defeatism are a
lready beginning to appear''. Demands for harder and heavier blows are again reported, and people are particularly anxious to see Italy "hammered into submission". Some believe that the R.A.F. blows, particularly on Southern Italy and the French aerodrome
s, are a prelude to invasion. (Four Regions)
\par 
\par The Berlin raid (August 23/24) was greeted with great satisfaction (Eight Regions), though pleasure was modified at first by surprise and regret at the high losses". However, it is felt, they were probably n
ot disproportionate to the numbers of planes involved or "the effect achieved, and insignificant compared with those of a land offensive". Demands for more and heavier bombing of Berlin continue... them go night after night give am}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 we've got'.
\par 
\par U.S.A.L.F.: Comparison is made between the bomber losses of the U.S.A.L.F., their claims of fighters shot down, and our own losses. People doubt if our own bombers are as well defended, and there are demands for their better equipment (Two Regions).

\par 
\par Rome: Th
e general view is still that we should reject the proposal to make Rome an open city, and that we should put no faith in Italian claims. "Badoglio cannot be relied on to clear out military objectives." People would like to see the bombing continued; and t
he Pope is criticised for his "squeamishness" about possible damage to religious buildings. It is again pointed out that "he did not appeal to the Germans to refrain from bombing London churches".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.10.11.13. 17 three provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 7. GERMANY'S DIFFICULTIES}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par Although a few people are "reluctant to be optimistic about it", many consider Himmler's app ointment as "a clear indication that German morale is getting shaky". Some go so far as to hope that the bad news from the wa
r fronts and our terrible air onslaught "may break it more suddenly then appearances suggest".
\par 
\par The unrest "all over occupied Europe" - "which must be increasing Germany's difficulties" - is watched with interest; as is also "the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 changing attitude of n
eutral countries". All this is felt to show that "confidence in, and fear of, Germany were fading". Specific reference is made to:
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid11883990 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
(a) Denmark: There is admiration for the courage of the Danes in revolting against Nazi oppression, and people hope that 
"we may be able to help thorn very soon". There is a tendency to interpret trouble hero as a sign either we intend to invade Denmark or that the Germans fear we will do so.
\par 
\par (b) Death of King Boris: Little is known}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 Balkan politics and people cannot tol
l whether "his removal will improve matters or not". Thor is no sympathy for King Boris, but a good deal of speculation about how he died: "'Most people. are convinced it was not a natural death."
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7484735 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (1.2,3.4.5.5SE.7.3.13.13)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 8. THE CONFERENCE}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par Speculation and comment about the Quebec. Conference are less this week; some people are describes "indifferent". Decline in interest is variously attributed to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7484735 lack of information, to people being "tired of talk" and anxious for action, and to disappo
intment that the war against Japan was the principle subject of discussion. Nevertheless many welcomed the conference as "foreshadowing a more active West Front offensive" are "hoping for big announcements".
\par 
\par 'The lack of Russian representation continues to be the cause of widespread re Fret and much anxiety (See Section 2).
\par 
\par Mrs. and Miss Churchill: Comment continues (Six Regions and Postal Censorship).
\par 
\par The Prime Minister's speech (to which no pubic reactions have yet been received)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 eagerly aw
aited by most people, many of whom hoped it would shed light on the various questions that are exercising their minds Its postponement caused disappointment, and much speculation as to the reason. Some thought it indicated "political awkwardness" and a fa
ilure to "make up their minds but most people thought it implied some new development,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 as the end of Italian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5447783  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 resistance, which Mr. Churchill was to announce.
\par 
\par President Roosevelt's speech at Ottawa (August 25) is said to have aroused some "mildly favourable" comment}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 not a great deal of interest.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par The revelations about Hess have been criticised (Five Regions) on two grounds:
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li426\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin426\itap0\pararsid11883990 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
(a) Scouts and their parents are indignant, in spite of the explanation. As a Welshman observes: "We take great news in a matter of fact way, while one remark out of place causes, widespread discussion - we truly are a mad.
\par 
\par (b) "The answer to the Hess mystery" was "refused to the House of Commons", but was given in Canada. 
\par The press handling of the Conference is criticised (Two Regions). }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
It is thought to have been "singularly contradictory and confusing' and is also blamed for giving prominence to "the holiday atmosphere at a time when people are anxious about Russia and want decisive action".
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-11\li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid7484735 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (1.2.3.4.5.6.7.8.10.11.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 13. 17  one Special, five provincial P.Cs.)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 9. ITALY}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par There is less talk this week about the political situation. A growing conviction that "only military pressure will drive Italy into submission" is allied to restlessness at our delay in i
nvading it. People wonder whether this delay is "yet another example of' our being too kind to the Wops" - "like the mistake we made laying off giving it to them when Musso fell".
\par 
\par While the majority arc in favour of 'nothing but unconditional surrender", a minority feel "such severe terms are likely to make them fight on".
\par 
\par British Prisoners of War: Anxiety continues at reports of their transfer from Italian to German hands.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (1.2.3.4.5.6.7.8.10.11.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 17 one Special, seven provincial P.Cs.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 10. SPAIN}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par There continues to be some speculation about the reasons for the Hoare-Franco talks: "Does it mean better relations with Spain, or has Franco been acting on behalf of Italy?"
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (2.4.6.7.13)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11883990 11. AMGOT}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par Some distrust of Amgot continues to be reported. It is described as "an undemocratic body"; people wonder why it is necessary, and where in the future "the exiled Allied Governments and their peoples will come in".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid92027 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (5.5SE.6.11)
\par 
\par 12. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid92027 THE FRENCH COMMITTEE FOR NATIONAL LIBERATION}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par There has boon satisfaction but very little comment at the recognition of the French Committee for National Liberation: "There is not much interest in the French at present."
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid92027 "The luke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 warm declaration by America" has caused comment, and she is also blamed for having caused the delay in giving this recognition.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid92027 13. FAR EAST }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par There continues to be little interest in the Far East, although some people wonder whether "there is to be a new offensive there as a result of the Quebec Conference".
\par 
\par The appointment of Lord Louis Mountbatten to the post of Supreme Commander in South-East is generally thought a good one (Four Regions): "People expect fireworks when he gets going". A minority doubt his being the right man for the post, howev
er. (Two Regions)
\par 
\par The appointment has been taken to show that we may be about to make a definite move possibly towards the recovery of Burma and Malaya. Some "puzzled" comment is recorded, however, that "such leaders are needed against Germany, before
 bothering with the Far East".
\par 
\par China: Sympathy for China and the desire to help her are reported from six Regions this week.
\par 
\par Prisoners of War in Japanese hands:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 names of missing relatives continue to be welcomed but it is asked whether "Geneva ca
nnot do more to get information?" Gratitude is expressed for the broadcast about prisoners of war in the Far East given on August 24th.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid92027 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (1.2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.8.10.11)
\par 
\par 14. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid92027 WAR AT SEA}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par There is again little comment on this subject, but satisfaction and pleasure continue at the successes against the U-boat menace.
\par 
\par The fine work of the Royal Navy, especially during the Sicilian campaign, is praised and there is great confidence "in its ability to deal with any situation".
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid92027 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (1.3.5.5SE.7.10)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid92027 15. HOLIDAYS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par There is loss talk of holidays this week. People' continue to believe in "the necessity of holiday travel"; they feel that those workers who have gone away have been wis
e to do so. "Those who did not go away, wish they had." Some criticism of the "Government's weakness and lack of foresight" end of the policy of holidays at home is again reported on familiar lines.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid92027 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (1.2.3.4.5.6.7.8)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid92027 16. THE COASTAL AREA BAN}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par Interest and speculation continue as to, the significance of the ban imposed on the South and South 'East coast. It is still believed that preparations for Invasion are being made in the area (Seven Regions). It is again suggested that it may be a bluff d
esigned to cover activity elsewhere or even a double bluff. 
\par 
\par Uncertainty as to the exact areas banned to visitors has been the cause of much telegraphing and telephoning. In the Southern Region; it is said that "the restriction notices are so worded as to be incomprehensible to the general public".
\par 
\par Rumours of troop movements come from the Regions involved in the ban.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid92027 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 (2.3.4.5.5SE.6.7.10)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid92027 17. BROADCASTING AND PRESENTATION OF NEWS }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
\par 
\par Satisfaction with news presentation by the B.B.C. and in the press is reported from four Regions. "People appear content to accept such official news as can be given at the moment."
\par 
\par Sensational press headlines are criticised in two Regions. Although qualified by the following news paragraphs, "they remain
 in the reader's mind" thus conveying the wrong impression. People are, however, said to be "on guard against press misrepresentation".
\par 
\par The B.B.C. is again criticised for the repetition of news (Two Regions). 
\par 
\par European News Service: Praise is again reported (Two Regions): "It is given with more colour than the Homo News".
\par 
\par Praise this week for: Commander Kimmmins' postscript on the King's visit to the Fleet. August 22 (Three Regions); the Russian commentary by Alexander Werth, August}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7484735 21 (Two Regions); the "Into Battle" series (Two Regions); War Commentaries (Two-Regions); The talk describing the construction of Mosquito pianos, August 24 (One Region)
\par 
\par Dr. J.J. Mallon's postscript (August 29) is criticised in three regional reports. It is though}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7484735 
we been an ''irritating pro-American advertisement" and "too sloppy". In one Region however, it is thought "likely to arouse real interest in American troops here".}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11892501 
\par 
